            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this carb calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This carb calculator estimates how many grams of carbohydrates
                you should eat per day using three steps:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Estimate your basal metabolic rate (BMR) using the Mifflin‑St
                  Jeor equation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Multiply BMR by an activity factor to get total daily energy
                  expenditure (TDEE).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply a carb range (grams per kilogram of body weight) based
                  on your goal and chosen carb style.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>1. BMR – Mifflin‑St Jeor equation</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>For men:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight (kg)} + 6.25 \times
                  \text{height (cm)} - 5 \times \text{age (years)} + 5\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>For women:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{BMR} = 10 \times \text{weight (kg)} + 6.25 \times
                  \text{height (cm)} - 5 \times \text{age (years)} - 161\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                BMR is the number of calories your body would burn in 24 hours
                at complete rest. It depends mainly on your fat‑free mass, which
                correlates with height, weight, sex, and age.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Activity factor and TDEE</h3>
              <p>
                We then multiply BMR by an activity factor to estimate your
                <strong>total daily energy expenditure (TDEE)</strong>:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Sedentary: 1.2</li>
                <li>Lightly active: 1.375</li>
                <li>Moderately active: 1.55</li>
                <li>Very active: 1.725</li>
                <li>Athlete / physical job: 1.9</li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \(\text{TDEE} = \text{BMR} \times \text{activity factor}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Goal calories</h3>
              <p>Your goal changes your calorie target:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weight loss:</strong> TDEE − 15–20% (we use −20% by
                  default).
                </li>
                <li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> TDEE (no change).</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Muscle gain:</strong> TDEE + 10–15% (we use +15% by
                  default).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \(\text{Goal calories} = \text{TDEE} \times (1 + \Delta)\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  where \(\Delta = -0.20\) for loss, \(0\) for maintenance, and
                  \(+0.15\) for gain.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Carb ranges by goal and style</h3>
              <p>
                Finally, we estimate your daily carbs in grams using a
                <strong>grams per kilogram (g/kg)</strong> approach. The
                calculator starts from a base range by goal and then adjusts it
                according to your chosen carb style.
              </p>

              <h4>Base carb ranges by goal</h4>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Weight loss:</strong> 2.0–3.0 g/kg</li>
                <li><strong>Maintenance:</strong> 3.0–4.0 g/kg</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Muscle gain / high training volume:</strong> 4.0–6.0
                  g/kg
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h4>Carb styles used in this calculator</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Very low‑carb:</strong> 0.5–1.0 g/kg (often &lt; 50
                  g/day for many people)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Low‑carb:</strong> 1.0–2.5 g/kg</li>
                <li><strong>Moderate:</strong> 3.0–4.5 g/kg</li>
                <li><strong>High‑carb:</strong> 4.5–7.0 g/kg</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                When you pick a style, we set a default value within these
                ranges but you can override it with the
                <strong>Custom g/kg</strong> field.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \(\text{Daily carbs (g)} = \text{body weight (kg)} \times
                  \text{carb factor (g/kg)}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Carb calories} = \text{Daily carbs (g)} \times 4\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How many carbs should I eat per day?</h2>
              <p>
                There is no single “perfect” carb target for everyone. Your
                ideal intake depends on your health status, activity level, body
                composition, and preferences. The ranges below are common
                starting points for adults:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Very low‑carb / ketogenic:</strong> typically &lt; 50
                  g/day
                </li>
                <li><strong>Low‑carb:</strong> about 50–130 g/day</li>
                <li><strong>Moderate‑carb:</strong> about 130–225 g/day</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>High‑carb:</strong> &gt; 225 g/day or &gt; 50–60% of
                  calories from carbs
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For most healthy, active adults, a
                <strong>moderate carb intake</strong> is sustainable and
                supports both performance and appetite control. Very low‑carb
                approaches can be useful for specific medical conditions under
                professional supervision.
              </p>

              <h3>Carbs for weight loss</h3>
              <p>
                Weight loss ultimately comes from a calorie deficit, not carbs
                alone. However, adjusting carbs can help you control hunger and
                blood sugar. Many people find success with:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>2–3 g/kg</strong> for general weight loss with regular
                  activity.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>1–2 g/kg</strong> if you prefer a lower‑carb approach.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>&lt; 1 g/kg</strong> (often &lt; 50 g/day) for
                  ketogenic diets, usually under medical guidance.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Carbs for muscle gain and performance</h3>
              <p>
                Carbohydrates are the primary fuel for high‑intensity training.
                If you lift weights, sprint, or play intense sports, higher carb
                intakes can support performance and recovery:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>3–5 g/kg</strong> for moderate training 3–5 days/week.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>4–7 g/kg</strong> for very active individuals or
                  endurance athletes.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                You can also <strong>time more of your carbs</strong> around
                workouts (before and after) to support performance and glycogen
                replenishment.
              </p>

              <h2>Net carbs vs total carbs</h2>
              <p>
                Many low‑carb and keto diets focus on
                <strong>net carbs</strong> rather than total carbs.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total carbs:</strong> all carbohydrates in a food
                  (sugars, starches, fiber, sugar alcohols).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Net carbs:</strong> total carbs minus fiber and some
                  sugar alcohols.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For blood sugar control and ketogenic diets, net carbs are often
                more relevant because fiber has minimal impact on blood glucose.
                For general health and weight management, tracking total carbs
                is usually sufficient.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator gives you a <strong>total carb target</strong>.
                If you choose to track net carbs, you can treat the result as a
                net carb target instead and subtract fiber from your foods
                accordingly.
              </p>

              <h2>Healthy carb sources</h2>
              <p>
                Regardless of your carb target, the <strong>quality</strong> of
                your carbs matters. Emphasize:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Vegetables (especially non‑starchy: leafy greens, broccoli,
                  peppers, etc.)
                </li>
                <li>Whole fruits (berries, apples, oranges, etc.)</li>
                <li>
                  Whole grains (oats, quinoa, brown rice, whole‑wheat bread)
                </li>
                <li>Legumes (beans, lentils, chickpeas)</li>
                <li>
                  Root vegetables (potatoes, sweet potatoes, beets) as
                  appropriate for your carb budget
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Limit highly refined carbs like sugary drinks, candy, pastries,
                and ultra‑processed snacks, which are easy to overeat and
                provide little nutrition.
              </p>

              <h2>Medical and safety disclaimer</h2>
              <p>
                This carb calculator is for
                <strong>general educational purposes only</strong>. It does not
                provide medical or dietetic advice and is not a substitute for
                consultation with a qualified healthcare professional or
                registered dietitian.
              </p>
              <p>
                You should seek professional guidance before making major
                changes to your carbohydrate intake if you:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Have diabetes, prediabetes, or insulin resistance</li>
                <li>Have kidney, liver, or pancreatic disease</li>
                <li>Are pregnant or breastfeeding</li>
                <li>Have a history of eating disorders</li>
                <li>
                  Take medications that affect blood sugar or blood pressure
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always monitor how you feel and adjust your diet gradually. If
                you experience dizziness, extreme fatigue, palpitations, or
                other concerning symptoms, contact a healthcare professional.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>
                Is it okay to eat fewer carbs than the calculator suggests?
              </h3>
              <p>
                You can eat fewer carbs than the suggested range, especially if
                you feel good and your energy, mood, and lab values are stable.
                However, going very low in carbs for long periods may not be
                appropriate for everyone. If you drop carbs significantly,
                consider increasing protein and healthy fats to keep calories
                adequate and discuss your plan with a professional.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I need to hit my carb target exactly every day?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Think of your carb target as a
                <strong>flexible range</strong>, not a strict rule. Day‑to‑day
                variation is normal. What matters most is your overall pattern
                over weeks and months and whether it supports your goals and
                health markers.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I split carbs across meals?</h3>
              <p>
                Many people do well spreading carbs fairly evenly across meals,
                with a slightly higher portion around workouts. The calculator
                gives per‑meal suggestions for 3, 4, and 5 meals per day; you
                can adjust based on your schedule and appetite.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this carb calculator if I have diabetes?</h3>
              <p>
                You can use it as a rough educational tool, but
                <strong>do not</strong> change your carbohydrate intake or
                medication regimen without guidance from your doctor or diabetes
                care team. Carb needs and medication adjustments for diabetes
                are highly individual.
              </p>
